# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proof-of-work
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific integrated circuit** (**ASIC** /ˈeɪsɪk/) is an integrated circuit (IC) chip customized for a particular use, rather than intended for general-purpose use, such as a chip designed to run in a digital voice recorder or a high-efficiency video codec.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Application-specific standard product chips are intermediate between ASICs and industry standard integrated circuits like the 7400 series or the 4000 series.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASIC chips are typically fabricated using metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) technology, as MOS integrated circuit chips.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As feature sizes have shrunk and chip design tools improved over the years, the maximum complexity (and hence functionality) possible in an ASIC has grown from 5,000 logic gates to over 100 million.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Modern ASICs often include entire microprocessors, memory blocks including ROM, RAM, EEPROM, flash memory and other large building blocks.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such an ASIC is often termed a SoC (system-on-chip).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers of digital ASICs often use a hardware description language (HDL), such as Verilog or VHDL, to describe the functionality of ASICs.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Field-programmable gate arrays (FPGA) are the modern-day technology improvement on breadboards, meaning that they are not made to be application-specific as opposed to ASICs.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Programmable logic blocks and programmable interconnects allow the same FPGA to be used in many different applications.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For smaller designs or lower production volumes, FPGAs may be more cost-effective than an ASIC design, even in production.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The non-recurring engineering (NRE) cost of an ASIC can run into the millions of dollars.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Therefore, device manufacturers typically prefer FPGAs for prototyping and devices with low production volume and ASICs for very large production volumes where NRE costs can be amortized across many devices.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By 1967, Ferranti and Interdesign were manufacturing early bipolar gate arrays.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In 1967, Fairchild Semiconductor introduced the Micromatrix family of bipolar diode–transistor logic (DTL) and transistor–transistor logic (TTL) arrays.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology opened the door to the broad commercialization of gate arrays.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The first CMOS gate arrays were developed by Robert Lipp, in 1974 for International Microcircuits, Inc.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) standard-cell technology was introduced by Fairchild and Motorola, under the trade names Micromosaic and Polycell, in the 1970s.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This technology was later successfully commercialized by VLSI Technology (founded 1979) and LSI Logic (1981).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A successful commercial application of gate array circuitry was found in the low-end 8-bit ZX81 and ZX Spectrum personal computers, introduced in 1981 and 1982.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These were used by Sinclair Research (UK) essentially as a low-cost I/O solution aimed at handling the computer's graphics.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Customization occurred by varying a metal interconnect mask.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate arrays had complexities of up to a few thousand gates; this is now called mid-scale integration.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Later versions became more generalized, with different base dies customized by both metal and polysilicon layers.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some base dies also include random-access memory (RAM) elements.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the mid-1980s, a designer would choose an ASIC manufacturer and implement their design using the design tools available from the manufacturer.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While third-party design tools were available, there was not an effective link from the third-party design tools to the layout and actual semiconductor process performance characteristics of the various ASIC manufacturers.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Most designers used factory-specific tools to complete the implementation of their designs.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] A solution to this problem, which also yielded a much higher density device, was the implementation of standard cells.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Every ASIC manufacturer could create functional blocks with known electrical characteristics, such as propagation delay, capacitance and inductance, that could also be represented in third-party tools.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is the utilization of these functional blocks to achieve very high gate density and good electrical performance.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard-cell design is intermediate between § Gate-array and semi-custom design and § Full-custom design in terms of its non-recurring engineering and recurring component costs as well as performance and speed of development (including time to market).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By the late 1990s, logic synthesis tools became available.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Such tools could compile HDL descriptions into a gate-level netlist.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Register-transfer level (RTL) design**: The design team constructs a description of an ASIC to achieve these goals using a hardware description language.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This process is similar to writing a computer program in a high-level language.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Functional verification**: Suitability for purpose is verified by functional verification.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This may include such techniques as logic simulation through test benches, formal verification, emulation, or creating and evaluating an equivalent pure software model, as in Simics.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Each verification technique has advantages and disadvantages, and most often several methods are used together for ASIC verification.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Unlike most FPGAs, ASICs cannot be reprogrammed once fabricated and therefore ASIC designs that are not completely correct are much more costly, increasing the need for full test coverage.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Logic synthesis**: Logic synthesis transforms the RTL design into a large collection called of lower-level constructs called standard cells.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These constructs are taken from a standard-cell library consisting of pre-characterized collections of logic gates performing specific functions.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The standard cells are typically specific to the planned manufacturer of the ASIC.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The resulting collection of standard cells and the needed electrical connections between them is called a gate-level netlist.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Placement**: The gate-level netlist is next processed by a placement tool which places the standard cells onto a region of an integrated circuit die representing the final ASIC.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The placement tool attempts to find an optimized placement of the standard cells, subject to a variety of specified constraints.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Routing**: An electronics routing tool takes the physical placement of the standard cells and uses the netlist to create the electrical connections between them.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Since the search space is large, this process will produce a "sufficient" rather than "globally optimal" solution.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The output is a file which can be used to create a set of photomasks enabling a semiconductor fabrication facility, commonly called a "fab" or "foundry" to manufacture physical integrated circuits.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Placement and routing are closely interrelated and are collectively called place and route in electronics design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] While Logic synthesis, Placement, and Routing are supported by electronic design automation tools, these stages require significant designer guidance and iteration.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Designers provide constraints derived from requirements engineering and RTL design, including timing requirements, floorplans, power budgets, and area restrictions.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Multiple tool iterations are typically necessary to meet performance, power, and area objectives, often requiring manual optimization and refinement that extends design cycle time considerably.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] **Sign-off**: Given the final layout, circuit extraction computes the parasitic resistances and capacitances.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In the case of a digital circuit, this will then be further mapped into delay information from which the circuit performance can be estimated, usually by static timing analysis.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This, and other final tests such as design rule checking and power analysis collectively called signoff are intended to ensure that the device will function correctly over all extremes of the process, voltage and temperature.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] When this testing is complete the photomask information is released for chip fabrication.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These steps, implemented with a level of skill common in the industry, almost always produce a final device that correctly implements the original design, unless flaws are later introduced by the physical fabrication process.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The design steps also called design flow, are common to standard product design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The significant difference is that standard-cell design uses the manufacturer's cell libraries that have been used in potentially hundreds of other design implementations and therefore are of much lower risk than a full custom design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Standard cells produce a design density that is cost-effective, and they can also integrate IP cores and static random-access memory (SRAM) effectively, unlike gate arrays.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate array design is a manufacturing method in which diffused layers, each consisting of transistors and other active devices, are predefined and electronics wafers containing such devices are "held in stock" or unconnected prior to the metallization stage of the fabrication process.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The physical design process defines the interconnections of these layers for the final device.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For most ASIC manufacturers, this consists of between two and nine metal layers with each layer running perpendicular to the one below it.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Non-recurring engineering costs are much lower than full custom designs, as photolithographic masks are required only for the metal layers.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Production cycles are much shorter, as metallization is a comparatively quick process; thereby accelerating time to market.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Gate-array ASICs are always a compromise between rapid design and performance as mapping a given design onto what a manufacturer held as a stock wafer never gives 100% circuit utilization.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often difficulties in routing the interconnect require migration onto a larger array device with a consequent increase in the piece part price.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] These difficulties are often a result of the layout EDA software used to develop the interconnect.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Pure, logic-only gate-array design is rarely implemented by circuit designers today, having been almost entirely replaced by field-programmable devices.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The most prominent of such devices are field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) which can be programmed by the user and thus offer minimal tooling charges, non-recurring engineering, only marginally increased piece part cost, and comparable performance.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Today, gate arrays are evolving into structured ASICs that consist of a large IP core like a CPU, digital signal processor units, peripherals, standard interfaces, integrated memories, SRAM, and a block of reconfigurable, uncommitted logic.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In their frequent usages in the field, the terms "gate array" and "semi-custom" are synonymous when referring to ASICs.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Process engineers more commonly use the term "semi-custom", while "gate-array" is more commonly used by logic (or gate-level) designers.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, full-custom ASIC design defines all the photolithographic layers of the device.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Full-custom design is used for both ASIC design and for standard product design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The benefits of full-custom design include reduced area (and therefore recurring component cost), performance improvements, and also the ability to integrate analog components and other pre-designed—and thus fully verified—components, such as microprocessor cores, that form a system on a chip.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The disadvantages of full-custom design can include increased manufacturing and design time, increased non-recurring engineering costs, more complexity in the computer-aided design (CAD) and electronic design automation systems, and a much higher skill requirement on the part of the design team.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For digital-only designs, however, "standard-cell" cell libraries, together with modern CAD systems, can offer considerable performance/cost benefits with low risk.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Automated layout tools are quick and easy to use and also offer the possibility to "hand-tweak" or manually optimize any performance-limiting aspect of the design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is designed by using basic logic gates, circuits or layout specially for a design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] This is effectively the same definition as a gate array.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What distinguishes a structured ASIC from a gate array is that in a gate array, the predefined metal layers serve to make manufacturing turnaround faster.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In a structured ASIC, the use of predefined metallization is primarily to reduce cost of the mask sets as well as making the design cycle time significantly shorter.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, in a cell-based or gate-array design the user must often design power, clock, and test structures themselves.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] By contrast, these are predefined in most structured ASICs and therefore can save time and expense for the designer compared to gate-array based designs.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Likewise, the design tools used for structured ASIC can be substantially lower cost and easier (faster) to use than cell-based tools, because they do not have to perform all the functions that cell-based tools do.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] In some cases, the structured ASIC vendor requires customized tools for their device (e.g., custom physical synthesis) be used, also allowing for the design to be brought into manufacturing more quickly.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Cell libraries of logical primitives are usually provided by the device manufacturer as part of the service.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Although they will incur no additional cost, their release will be covered by the terms of a non-disclosure agreement (NDA) and they will be regarded as intellectual property by the manufacturer.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Usually, their physical design will be pre-defined so they could be termed "hard macros".
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] What most engineers understand as "intellectual property" are IP cores, designs purchased from a third-party as sub-components of a larger ASIC.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] They may be provided in the form of a hardware description language (often termed a "soft macro"), or as a fully routed design that could be printed directly onto an ASIC's mask (often termed a "hard macro").
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Many organizations now sell such pre-designed cores – CPUs, Ethernet, USB or telephone interfaces – and larger organizations may have an entire department or division to produce cores for the rest of the organization.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The company ARM *only* sells IP cores, making it a fabless manufacturer.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Additionally, open-source hardware organizations such as OpenCores are collecting free IP cores, paralleling the open-source software movement in hardware design.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Soft macros are often process-independent (i.e. they can be fabricated on a wide range of manufacturing processes and different manufacturers).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Hard macros are process-limited and usually further design effort must be invested to migrate (port) to a different process or manufacturer.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Some manufacturers and IC design houses offer multi-project wafer service (MPW) as a method of obtaining low cost prototypes.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Often called shuttles, these MPWs, containing several designs, run at regular, scheduled intervals on a "cut and go" basis, usually with limited liability on the part of the manufacturer.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The contract involves delivery of bare dies or the assembly and packaging of a handful of devices.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The service usually involves the supply of a physical design database (i.e. masking information or pattern generation (PG) tape).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] The manufacturer is often referred to as a "silicon foundry" due to the low involvement it has in the process.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] An **application-specific standard product** (**ASSP**) is an integrated circuit that implements a specific function that appeals to a wide market.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] As opposed to ASICs that combine a collection of functions and are designed by or for one customer, ASSPs are available as off-the-shelf components.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASSPs are used in all industries, from automotive to communications.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] For example, two ICs that might or might not be considered ASICs are a controller chip for a PC and a chip for a modem.
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Both of these examples are specific to an application (which is typical of an ASIC) but are sold to many different system vendors (which is typical of standard parts).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] ASICs such as these are sometimes called application-specific standard products (ASSPs).
[src:proof-of-work/application-specific-integrated-circuit] Examples of ASSPs are encoding/decoding chip, Ethernet network interface controller chip and flash memory controller chip.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin works through the collaboration of computers, each of which acts as a node in the peer-to-peer bitcoin network.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Each node maintains an independent copy of a public distributed ledger of transactions, called a blockchain, without central oversight.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Transactions are validated through the use of cryptography, preventing one person from spending another person's bitcoin, as long as the owner of the bitcoin keeps certain sensitive data secret.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Consensus between nodes about the content of the blockchain is achieved using a computationally intensive process based on proof of work, called mining, which is performed by purpose-built computers.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Mining consumes large quantities of electricity, with surveyed miners reporting that 52% of their electricity use came from sustainable energy sources, and has been criticized for its environmental impact.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Before bitcoin, several digital cash technologies were released, starting with David Chaum's ecash in the 1980s.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The idea that solutions to computational puzzles could have some value was first proposed by cryptographers Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor in 1992.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The concept was independently rediscovered by Adam Back who developed Hashcash, a proof-of-work scheme for spam control in 1997.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The first proposals for distributed digital scarcity-based cryptocurrencies came from cypherpunks Wei Dai (b-money) and Nick Szabo (bit gold) in 1998.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2004, Hal Finney developed the first currency based on reusable proof of work.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] These various attempts were not successful: Chaum's concept required centralized control and no banks wanted to sign on, Hashcash had no protection against double-spending, while b-money and bit gold were not resistant to Sybil attacks.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The domain name *bitcoin.org* was registered on 18 August 2008.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] On 31 October 2008, a link to a white paper authored by Satoshi Nakamoto titled *Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System* was posted to a cryptography mailing list.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to computer scientist Arvind Narayanan, all individual components of bitcoin originated in earlier academic literature.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nakamoto's innovation was their complex interplay which resulted in the first decentralized, Sybil resistant, Byzantine fault tolerant digital cash system, that would eventually be referred to as the first blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nakamoto's paper was not peer-reviewed and was initially ignored by academics, who argued that it could not work.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nakamoto released bitcoin as open-source software.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] On 3 January 2009, the bitcoin network was created when Nakamoto mined the starting block of the chain, known as the *genesis block*.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Embedded in this block was the text "The Times 03/Jan/2009 Chancellor on brink of second bailout for banks", which is the date and headline of an issue of *The Times* newspaper.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nine days later, Hal Finney received the first bitcoin transaction: ten bitcoins from Nakamoto.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Wei Dai and Nick Szabo were also early supporters.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] On May 22, 2010, the first known commercial transaction using bitcoin occurred when programmer Laszlo Hanyecz bought two Papa John's pizzas for ₿10,000, in what would later be celebrated as "Bitcoin Pizza Day".
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Satoshi tasked Finnish developer and early Bitcoin contributor Martti Malmi with creating content for the bitcoin.org website.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Blockchain analysts estimate that Nakamoto had mined about one million bitcoins before he disappeared in 2010 and handed the network alert key and control of the code repository over to Gavin Andresen.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Andresen later became lead developer at the Bitcoin Foundation, an organization founded in September 2012 to promote bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] After early "proof-of-concept" transactions, the first major users of bitcoin were black markets, such as the dark web Silk Road.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] During its 30 months of existence, beginning in February 2011, Silk Road exclusively accepted bitcoins as payment, transacting ₿9.9 million, worth about $214 million.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In May 2013, US authorities seized the unregistered exchange Mt.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In June 2013, the US Drug Enforcement Administration seized ₿11.02 from an individual attempting to use them to purchase illicit drugs.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This marked the first time a government agency had seized bitcoins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The FBI seized about ₿30,000 in October 2013 from Silk Road, following the arrest of its founder Ross Ulbricht.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In December 2013, the People's Bank of China prohibited Chinese financial institutions from using bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] After the announcement, the value of bitcoin dropped, and Baidu no longer accepted bitcoins for certain services.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Buying real-world goods with any virtual currency had been illegal in China since at least 2009.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Research produced by the University of Cambridge estimated that in 2017, there were 2.9 to 5.8 million unique users using a cryptocurrency wallet, most of them using bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In August 2017, the SegWit software upgrade was activated.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Segwit was intended to support the Lightning Network as well as improve scalability.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] SegWit opponents, who supported larger blocks as a scalability solution, forked to create Bitcoin Cash, one of many forks of bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In December 2017, the first futures on bitcoin was introduced by the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME).
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In February 2018, the price crashed after China imposed a complete ban on bitcoin trading.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The percentage of bitcoin trading in the Chinese renminbi fell from over 90% in September 2017 to less than 1% in June 2018.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] During the same year, bitcoin prices were negatively affected by several hacks or thefts from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2020, some major companies and institutions started to acquire bitcoin: MicroStrategy invested $250 million in bitcoin as a treasury reserve asset, Square, Inc., $50 million, and MassMutual, $100 million.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In November 2020, PayPal added support for bitcoin in the US.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In February 2021, bitcoin's market capitalization reached $1 trillion for the first time.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In November 2021, the Taproot soft-fork upgrade was activated, adding support for Schnorr signatures, improved functionality of smart contracts and Lightning Network.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Before, bitcoin only used a custom elliptic curve with the ECDSA algorithm to produce signatures.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In September 2021, bitcoin became legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In October 2021, the first bitcoin futures exchange-traded fund (ETF), called BITO, from ProShares was approved by the SEC and listed on the CME.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In early 2022, during the Canadian trucker protests opposing COVID-19 vaccine mandates, organizers turned to bitcoin to receive donations after traditional financial platforms restricted access to funding.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Proponents highlighted bitcoin's use as a tool for fundraising in situations where access to conventional financial systems may be restricted.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In May and June 2022, the bitcoin price fell following the collapses of TerraUSD, a stablecoin, and the Celsius Network, a cryptocurrency loan company.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2023, ordinals—non-fungible tokens (NFTs)—on bitcoin, went live.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of June 2023, River Financial estimated that bitcoin had 81.7 million users, about 1% of the global population.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In January 2024, the first 11 US spot bitcoin ETFs began trading, offering direct exposure to bitcoin for the first time on American stock exchanges.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In December 2024, bitcoin price reached $100,000 for the first time, as US president-elect Donald Trump promised to make the US the "crypto capital of the planet" and to stockpile bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The same month, BlackRock, the world's largest asset manager, recommended investors to allocate up to 2% of their portfolio to bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of 2025, the Salvadoran government continues to describe Bitcoin as legal tender under the 2021 Bitcoin Law; however, a January 2025 reform removed obligations for businesses and the government to accept it, so many analysts regard its legal-tender status as effectively ended in practice.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In March 2025, President Trump signed an executive order to establish a strategic bitcoin reserve.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Later that year, some U.S. states, such as Texas and New Hampshire also instituted strategic bitcoin reserves, and the Czech National Bank bought less than €1 million in a "test portfolio".
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin logos made by Satoshi Nakamoto in 2009 (left) and 2010 (right).
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The unit of account of the bitcoin system is the *bitcoin*.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] It is most commonly represented with the symbol ₿ designed in 2010 and the currency code BTC.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] However, the BTC code does not conform to ISO 4217 as BT is the country code of Bhutan, and ISO 4217 requires the first letter used in global commodities to be 'X'.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] XBT, a code that conforms to ISO 4217 though not officially part of it, is used by Bloomberg L.P.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] No uniform capitalization convention exists; some sources use *Bitcoin*, capitalized, to refer to the technology and network, and *bitcoin*, lowercase, for the unit of account.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The *Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary* and the *Oxford Advanced Learner's Dictionary* use the capitalized and lowercase variants without distinction.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] One bitcoin is divisible to eight decimal places.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Units for smaller amounts of bitcoin are the millibitcoin (mBTC), equal to 1⁄1000 bitcoin, and the satoshi (sat), representing 1⁄100000000 (one hundred millionth) bitcoin, the smallest amount possible.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As a decentralized system, bitcoin operates without a central authority or single administrator, so that anyone can create a new bitcoin address and transact without needing any approval.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This is accomplished through a specialized distributed ledger called a *blockchain* that records bitcoin transactions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The blockchain is implemented as an ordered list of *blocks*.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Each block contains a SHA-256 hash of the previous block, chaining them in chronological order.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The blockchain is maintained by a peer-to-peer network.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Individual blocks, public addresses, and transactions within blocks are public information, and can be examined using a blockchain explorer.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nodes validate and broadcast transactions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Each node maintains a copy of the blockchain for ownership verification.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] A new block is created every 10 minutes on average, updating the blockchain across all nodes without central oversight.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This process tracks bitcoin spending, ensuring each bitcoin is spent only once.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Unlike a traditional ledger that tracks physical currency, bitcoins exist digitally as unspent outputs of transactions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In the blockchain, bitcoins are linked to specific strings called addresses.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Most often, an address encodes a hash of a single public key.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Creating such an address involves generating a random private key and then computing the corresponding address.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This process is almost instant, but the reverse (finding the private key for a given address) is nearly impossible.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Publishing such a bitcoin address does not risk its private key, and it is extremely unlikely to accidentally generate a used key with funds.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] To use bitcoins, owners need their private key to digitally sign transactions, which are verified by the network using the public key, keeping the private key secret.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] An address may encode the hash of a bitcoin script that specifies more complex requirements to spend the funds.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] One common example is "multisig", in which multiple distinct private keys must mutually sign any transaction that attempts to spend the funds.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin transactions use a Forth-like scripting language, involving one or more inputs and outputs.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] When sending bitcoins, a user specifies the recipients' addresses and the amount for each output.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This allows sending bitcoins to several recipients in a single transaction.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] To prevent double-spending, each input must refer to a previous unspent output in the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Using multiple inputs is similar to using multiple coins in a cash transaction.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As in a cash transaction, the sum of inputs can exceed the intended sum of payments.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In such a case, an additional output can return the change back to the payer.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Unallocated input satoshis in the transaction become the transaction fee.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Losing a private key means losing access to the bitcoins, with no other proof of ownership accepted by the protocol.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] For instance, in 2013, a user lost ₿7,500, valued at US$7.5 million, by accidentally discarding a hard drive with the private key.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] It is estimated that around 20% of all bitcoins are lost.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The private key must also be kept secret as its exposure, such as through a data breach, can lead to theft of the associated bitcoins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of December 2017, approximately ₿980,000 had been stolen from cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Miners don't directly act as nodes, but do communicate with nodes.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The mining process in bitcoin involves maintaining the blockchain through computer processing power.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Miners group and broadcast new transactions into blocks, which are then verified by the network.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Each block must contain a proof of work (PoW) to be accepted, involving finding a nonce number that, combined with the block content, produces a hash numerically smaller than the network's *difficulty target*.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This PoW is simple to verify but hard to generate, requiring many attempts.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] PoW forms the basis of bitcoin's consensus mechanism.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The difficulty of generating a block is deterministically adjusted based on the mining power on the network by changing the difficulty target, which is recalibrated every 2,016 blocks (approximately two weeks) to maintain an average time of ten minutes between new blocks.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The process requires significant computational power and specialized hardware.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Miners who successfully create a new block with a valid nonce can collect transaction fees from the included transactions and a fixed reward in bitcoins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] To claim this reward, a special transaction called a *coinbase* is included in the block, with the miner as the payee.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] All bitcoins in existence have been created through this type of transaction.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This reward is halved every 210,000 blocks until ₿21 million have been issued in total, which is expected to occur around the year 2140.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Afterward, miners will only earn from transaction fees.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] These fees are determined by the transaction's size and the amount of data stored, measured in satoshis per byte.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The proof of work system and the chaining of blocks make blockchain modifications very difficult, as altering one block requires changing all subsequent blocks.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As more blocks are added, modifying older blocks becomes increasingly challenging.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In case of disagreement, nodes trust the longest chain, which required the greatest amount of effort to produce.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] To tamper or censor the ledger, one needs to control the majority of the global hashrate.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The high cost required to reach this level of computational power secures the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The environmental impact of bitcoin mining is controversial and has attracted the attention of regulators, leading to restrictions or incentives in various jurisdictions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of 2025, a non-peer-reviewed study by the Cambridge Centre for Alternative Finance (CCAF) estimated that bitcoin mining represented 0.5% of global electricity consumption and 0.08% of world greenhouse gas emissions, comparable to Slovakia's emissions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] About half of the electricity used is generated through fossil fuels.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Moreover, mining hardware's short lifespan results in electronic waste.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In October 2025, the US was the largest mining country with 38% of the global bitcoin mining market share, followed by Russia (16%) and China (14%, despite all cryptocurrency trading and mining being banned there in 2021).
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin is pseudonymous, with funds linked to addresses, not real-world identities.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] While the owners of these addresses are not directly identified, all transactions are public on the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Patterns of use, like spending coins from multiple inputs, can hint at a common owner.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Public data can sometimes be matched with known address owners.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin exchanges might also need to collect personal data as per legal requirements.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] For enhanced privacy, users can generate a new address for each transaction.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In the bitcoin network, each bitcoin is treated equally, ensuring basic fungibility.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] However, users and applications can choose to differentiate between bitcoins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] While wallets and software treat all bitcoins the same, each bitcoin's transaction history is recorded on the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This public record allows for chain analysis, where users can identify and potentially reject bitcoins from controversial sources.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Gox froze accounts containing bitcoins identified as stolen.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin wallets were the first cryptocurrency wallets, enabling users to store the information necessary to transact bitcoins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The first wallet program, simply named *Bitcoin*, and sometimes referred to as the *Satoshi client*, was released in 2009 by Nakamoto as open-source software.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin Core is among the best known clients.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Forks of Bitcoin Core exist such as Bitcoin Unlimited.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Wallets can be full clients, with a full copy of the blockchain to check the validity of mined blocks, or lightweight clients, just to send and receive transactions without a local copy of the entire blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Third-party internet services, called online wallets or hot wallets, store users' credentials on their servers, making them susceptible of hacks.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Cold storage protects bitcoins from such hacks by keeping private keys offline, either through specialized hardware wallets or paper printouts.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nakamoto limited the block size to one megabyte.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The limited block size and frequency can lead to delayed processing of transactions, increased fees and a bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The Lightning Network, a second-layer routing network, is a potential scaling solution.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Research shows a trend towards centralization in bitcoin as miners join pools for stable income.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] If a single miner or pool controls more than 50% of the hashing power, it would allow them to censor transactions and double-spend coins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2014, mining pool Ghash.io reached 51% mining power, causing safety concerns, but later voluntarily capped its power at 39.99% for the benefit of the whole network.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] A few entities also dominate other parts of the ecosystem such as the client software, online wallets, and simplified payment verification (SPV) clients.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Sociologist Nigel Dodd argues that the essence of the bitcoin ideology is to remove money from social, as well as governmental, control.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] *The Economist* describes bitcoin as "a techno-anarchist project to create an online version of cash, a way for people to transact without the possibility of interference from malicious governments or banks".
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] These philosophical ideas initially attracted libertarians and anarchists.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Money serves three purposes: a store of value, a medium of exchange, and a unit of account.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to *The Economist* in 2014, bitcoin functions best as a medium of exchange.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2015, *The Economist* noted that bitcoins had three qualities useful in a currency: they are "hard to earn, limited in supply and easy to verify".
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] However, a 2018 assessment by *The Economist* stated that cryptocurrencies met none of these three criteria.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Per some researchers, as of 2015, bitcoin functions more as a payment system than as a currency.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Shiller wrote that bitcoin has potential as a unit of account for measuring the relative value of goods, as with Chile's Unidad de Fomento, but that "Bitcoin in its present form... doesn't really solve any sensible economic problem".
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The legal status of bitcoin varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Because of its decentralized nature and its global presence, regulating bitcoin is difficult.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] However, the use of bitcoin can be criminalized, and shutting down exchanges and the peer-to-peer economy in a given country would constitute a de facto ban.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The use of bitcoin by criminals has attracted the attention of financial regulators, legislative bodies, and law enforcement.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Nobel-prize winning economist Joseph Stiglitz says that bitcoin's anonymity encourages money laundering and other crimes.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] This is the main justification behind bitcoin bans.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of November 2021, nine countries applied an absolute ban (Algeria, Bangladesh, China, Egypt, Iraq, Morocco, Nepal, Qatar, and Tunisia) while another 42 countries had an implicit ban.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to Harvard Professor Kenneth Rogoff as of 2025, bitcoin is rarely used in regular transactions with merchants, but is popular in the informal economy and for criminal activities.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Prices are not usually quoted in bitcoin and trades involve conversions into fiat currencies.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Commonly cited reasons for not using bitcoin include high costs, the inability to process chargebacks, high price volatility, long transaction times, and transaction fees (especially for small purchases).
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] *Bloomberg* reported that bitcoin was being used for large-item purchases on the site Overstock.com and for cross-border payments to freelancers.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of 2015, there was little sign of bitcoin use in international remittances despite high fees charged by banks and Western Union.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] From September 2021 until January 2025, the Bitcoin Law made bitcoin a legal tender currency in El Salvador, alongside the US dollar.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The adoption had been criticized internationally and within El Salvador.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2022, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) urged El Salvador to reverse its decision.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of 2022, the use of Bitcoin in El Salvador remained low: 80% of businesses refused to accept it.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2025, El Salvador's government revoked bitcoin's status as legal tender currency in order to comply with conditions set by the IMF for a loan.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] El Salvador still describes bitcoin as "legal tender", but its acceptance is no longer obligitory (as it is with the US dollar) and the El Salvador government no longer accepts bitcoin for payment of taxes or fees.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In April 2022, the Central African Republic (CAR) adopted bitcoin as legal tender alongside the CFA franc, but repealed the reform one year later.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin is also used by some governments.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] For instance, the Iranian government initially opposed cryptocurrencies, but later began using them to circumvent sanctions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Since 2020, Iran has required local bitcoin miners to sell bitcoin to the Central Bank of Iran, allowing the central bank to use it for imports.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Some constituent states and local governments also accept tax payments in bitcoin, including Colorado in the US and Zug and Lugano in Switzerland.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of 2023, the US government owned more than $5 billion worth of seized bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of 2018, the overwhelming majority of bitcoin transactions took place on cryptocurrency exchanges.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Since 2014, regulated bitcoin funds also allow exposure to the asset or to futures as an investment.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin is used as a store of value: individuals and companies such as the Winklevoss twins and Elon Musk's companies SpaceX and Tesla have each bought and sold hundreds of millions of dollars worth of bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin wealth is highly concentrated, with 0.01% holding 27% of in-circulation currency, as of 2021.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] As of March 2025, El Salvador had $550 million worth of bitcoin in its international reserves, about 6,102 coins.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin, along with other cryptocurrencies, has been described as an economic bubble by several economists, including Nobel Prize in Economics laureates, such as Joseph Stiglitz, James Heckman, and Paul Krugman.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Another recipient of the prize, Robert Shiller, argues that bitcoin is rather a fad that may become an asset class.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] He describes its price growth as an "epidemic", driven by contagious narratives.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2024, Jean Tirole, also Nobel laureate, described bitcoin as a "pure bubble" as its intrinsic value is zero.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to him, some bubbles are long-lasting such as gold and fiat currencies, and it is impossible to predict whether bitcoin would implode like other financial bubbles or become an alternative to gold.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The same year, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell described bitcoin as a digital competitor to gold but not to the dollar as he argued it is a highly volatile speculative asset not used as a form of payment.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2025, Kenneth Rogoff claimed that Krugman was wrong and that Bitcoin had value as it is competing with the dollar to become the means of exchange of the underground economy which represents 20% of the world's GDP.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to Rogoff, bitcoin is "the ideal currency for a more fragmented and uncertain global landscape" and it could become appealing to emerging-market central banks as a "politically neutral" reserve currency.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to research published in the *International Review of Financial Analysis* in 2018, bitcoin as an asset is highly volatile and does not behave like any other conventional asset.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] According to one 2022 analysis published in *The Journal of Alternative Investments*, bitcoin was less volatile than oil, silver, US Treasuries, and 190 stocks in the S&P 500 during and after the 2020 stock market crash.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The term *hodl* was created in December 2013 for holding bitcoin rather than selling it during periods of volatility.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] In 2014, economist Nouriel Roubini described bitcoin as a Ponzi scheme.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Legal scholar Eric Posner disagrees, however, as "a real Ponzi scheme takes fraud; bitcoin, by contrast, seems more like a collective delusion".
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] A 2014 World Bank report also concluded that bitcoin was not a deliberate Ponzi scheme.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin markets operate 24 hours a day, seven days a week, contrasting with traditional financial markets that have fixed trading hours.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] Bitcoin prices show much higher volatility and respond strongly to both regulatory changes and market events.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The volume of bitcoin trading can fluctuate considerably among various exchanges and geographic regions.
[src:proof-of-work/bitcoin] The daily transaction volume of bitcoin across all exchanges typically reaches $50 billion as of 2025.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The Ethereum network began by using a consensus mechanism that involved **Proof-of-work (PoW)**.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] This allowed the nodes of the Ethereum network to agree on the state of all information recorded on the Ethereum blockchain and prevented certain kinds of economic attacks.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] However, Ethereum switched off proof-of-work in 2022 and started using proof-of-stake instead.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Ethereum no longer uses proof-of-work as part of its consensus mechanism.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] To better understand this page, we recommend you first read up on transactions, blocks, and consensus mechanisms.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Nakamoto consensus, which utilizes proof-of-work, is the mechanism that once allowed the decentralized Ethereum network to come to consensus (i.e., all nodes agree) on things like account balances and the order of transactions.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] This prevented users from "double spending" their coins and ensured that the Ethereum chain was tremendously difficult to attack or manipulate.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] These security properties now come from proof-of-stake instead using the consensus mechanism known as Gasper.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Proof-of-work is the underlying algorithm that sets the difficulty and rules for the work miners do on proof-of-work blockchains.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] It's the act of adding valid blocks to the chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] This is important because the chain's length helps the network follow the correct fork of the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The more "work" done, the longer the chain, and the higher the block number, the more certain the network can be of the current state of things.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Ethereum transactions are processed into blocks.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] This block data was directly related to proof-of-work.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The proof-of-work protocol, Ethash, required miners to go through an intense race of trial and error to find the nonce for a block.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Only blocks with a valid nonce could be added to the chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] When racing to create a block, a miner repeatedly put a dataset, that could only be obtained by downloading and running the full chain (as a miner does), through a mathematical function.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The dataset was used to generate a mixHash below a target that is dictated by the block difficulty.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The best way to do this is through trial and error.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The difficulty determined the target for the hash.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The lower the target, the smaller the set of valid hashes.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Once generated, this was incredibly easy for other miners and clients to verify.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Even if one transaction were to change, the hash would be completely different, signalling fraud.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] But proof-of-work as a process was also a big deterrent to attacking the chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Miners were incentivized to do this work on the main Ethereum chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] There was little incentive for a subset of miners to start their own chain—it undermines the system.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Blockchains rely on having a single state as a source of truth.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The objective of proof-of-work was to extend the chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] The longest chain was most believable as the valid one because it had the most computational work done to generate it.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Within Ethereum's PoW system, it was nearly impossible to create new blocks that erase transactions, create fake ones, or maintain a second chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] That's because a malicious miner would have needed to always solve the block nonce faster than everyone else.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] To consistently create malicious yet valid blocks, a malicious miner would have needed over 51% of the network mining power to beat everyone else.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] That amount of "work" requires a lot of expensive computing power and the energy spent might even have outweighed the gains made in an attack.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Proof-of-work was also responsible for issuing new currency into the system and incentivizing miners to do the work.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Since the Constantinople upgrade, miners who successfully create a block were rewarded with two freshly minted ETH and part of the transaction fees.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Ommer blocks were valid blocks created by a miner practically at the same time as another miner created the canonical block, which was ultimately determined by which chain was built on top of first.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Ommer blocks usually happened due to network latency.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] A transaction has "finality" on Ethereum when it's part of a block that can't change.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Because miners worked in a decentralized way, two valid blocks could be mined at the same time.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Eventually, one of these chains became the accepted chain after subsequent blocks were mined and added to it, making it longer.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] To complicate things further, transactions rejected on the temporary fork may not have been included in the accepted chain.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] So finality refers to the time you should wait before considering a transaction irreversible.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Under the previous proof-of-work Ethereum, the more blocks were mined on top of a specific block `N`, the higher confidence that the transactions in `N` were successful and would not be reverted.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Now, with proof-of-stake, finalization is an explicit, rather than probabilistic, property of a block.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] A major criticism of proof-of-work is the amount of energy output required to keep the network safe.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] To maintain security and decentralization, Ethereum on proof-of-work consumed large amounts of energy.
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] Shortly before switching to proof-of-stake, Ethereum miners were collectively consuming about 70 TWh/yr (about the same as the Czech Republic - according to digiconomist (opens in a new tab) on 18-July-2022).
[src:proof-of-work/consensus-mechanisms-pow] At a high level, proof-of-stake has the same end goal as proof-of-work: to help the decentralized network reach consensus securely.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The idea "...to require a user to compute a moderately hard, but not intractable function..." was proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hashcash is a cryptographic hash-based proof-of-work algorithm that requires a selectable amount of work to compute, but the proof can be verified efficiently.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] For email uses, a textual encoding of a hashcash stamp is added to the header of an email to prove the sender has expended a modest amount of CPU time calculating the stamp prior to sending the email.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] In other words, as the sender has taken a certain amount of time to generate the stamp and send the email, it is unlikely that they are a spammer.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The receiver can, at negligible computational cost, verify that the stamp is valid.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] However, the only known way to find a header with the necessary properties is brute force, trying random values until the answer is found; though testing an individual string is easy, satisfactory answers are rare enough that it will require a substantial number of tries to find the answer.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The hypothesis is that spammers, whose business model relies on their ability to send large numbers of emails with very little cost per message, will cease to be profitable if there is even a small cost for each spam they send.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Receivers can verify whether a sender made such an investment and use the results to help filter email.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The header contains the recipient's email address, the date of the message, and information proving that the required computation has been performed.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The presence of the recipient's email address requires that a different header be computed for each recipient.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The date allows the recipient to record headers received recently and to ensure that the header is unique to the email message.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The sender prepares a header and appends a counter value initialized to a random number.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] It then computes the 160-bit SHA-1 hash of the header.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] If the first 20 bits (i.e. the 5 most significant hex digits) of the hash are all zeros, then this is an acceptable header.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] If not, then the sender increments the counter and tries the hash again.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Out of 2160 possible hash values, there are 2140 hash values that satisfy this criterion.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Thus the chance of randomly selecting a header that will have 20 zeros as the beginning of the hash is 1 in 220 (approx.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The number of times that the sender needs to try to get a valid hash value is modeled by geometric distribution.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hence the sender will on average have to try 220 values to find a valid header.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Given reasonable estimates of the time needed to compute the hash, this would take about one second to find.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] No more efficient method than this brute force approach is known to find a valid header.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] A normal user on a desktop PC would not be significantly inconvenienced by the processing time required to generate the Hashcash string.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] However, spammers would suffer significantly due to the large number of spam messages sent by them.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] If the hash string passes all of these tests, it is considered a valid hash string.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] All of these tests take far less time and disk space than receiving the body content of the e-mail.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The time needed to compute such a hash partial preimage is exponential with the number of zero bits.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] So additional zero bits can be added (doubling the amount of time needed to compute a hash with each additional zero bit) until it is too expensive for spammers to generate valid header lines.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Confirming that the header is valid is much faster and always takes the same amount of time, no matter how many zero bits are required for a valid header, since this requires only a single hashing operation.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The Hashcash system has the advantage over micropayment proposals applying to legitimate e-mail that no real money is involved.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Neither the sender nor recipient need to pay, thus the administrative issues involved with any micropayment system and moral issues related to charging for e-mail are entirely avoided.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] On the other hand, as Hashcash requires potentially significant computational resources to be expended on each e-mail being sent, it is somewhat difficult to tune the ideal amount of average time one wishes clients to expend computing a valid header.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] This can mean sacrificing accessibility from low-end embedded systems or else running the risk of hostile hosts not being challenged enough to provide an effective filter from spam.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hashcash is also fairly simple to implement in mail user agents and spam filters.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hashcash can be incrementally deployed—the extra Hashcash header is ignored when it is received by mail clients that do not understand it.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] One plausible analysis concluded that only one of the following cases is likely: either non-spam e-mail will get stuck due to lack of processing power of the sender, or spam e-mail is bound to still get through.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Examples of each include, respectively, a centralized e-mail topology (like a mailing list), in which some server is to send an enormous number of *legitimate* e-mails, and botnets or cluster farms with which spammers can increase their processing power enormously.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] E.g., botnets may expire faster because users notice the high CPU load and take counter-measures, and mailing list servers can be registered in white lists on the subscribers' hosts and thus be relieved from the hashcash challenges.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Another projected problem is that computers continue to get faster according to Moore's law.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] So the difficulty of the calculations required must be increased over time.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] However, developing countries can be expected to use older hardware, which means that they will find it increasingly difficult to participate in the e-mail system.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] This also applies to lower-income individuals in developed countries who cannot afford the latest hardware.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Like hashcash, cryptocurrencies use a hash function as their proof-of-work system.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The rise of cryptocurrency has created a demand for ASIC-based mining machines.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Although most cryptocurrencies use the SHA-256 hash function, the same ASIC technology could be used to create hashcash solvers that are three orders of magnitude faster than a consumer CPU, reducing the computational hurdle for spammers.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] In contrast to hashcash in mail applications that relies on recipients to set manually an amount of work intended to *deter* malicious senders, the Bitcoin cryptocurrency network employs a different hash-based proof-of-work challenge to *enable* competitive Bitcoin mining.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] A Bitcoin miner runs a computer program that collects unconfirmed transactions from users on the network.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Together, these can form a "block" and earn a payment to the miner, but a block is only accepted by the network if its hash meets the network's difficulty target.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Thus, as in hashcash, miners must discover by brute force the "nonce" that, when included in the block, results in an acceptable hash.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hashcash was used as a potential solution for false positives with automated spam filtering systems, as legitimate users will rarely be inconvenienced by the extra time it takes to mine a stamp.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] SpamAssassin was able to check for Hashcash stamps since version 2.70 until version 3.4.2, assigning a negative score (i.e. less likely to be spam) for valid, unspent Hashcash stamps.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] However, although the hashcash plugin is on by default, it still needs to be configured with a list of address patterns that must match against the Hashcash resource field before it will be used.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Support was removed from SpamAssassin's trunk on 2019-06-26, affecting version 3.4.3 and beyond.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The Penny Post software project on SourceForge implements Hashcash in the Mozilla Thunderbird email client.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The project is named for the historical availability of conventional mailing services that cost the sender just one penny; see Penny Post for information about such mailing services in history.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Microsoft also designed and implemented a now deprecated open specification called "Email Postmark".
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] This was part of Microsoft's Coordinated Spam Reduction Initiative (CSRI).
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The Microsoft email postmark variant of Hashcash is implemented in the Microsoft mail infrastructure components Exchange, Outlook, and Hotmail.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The format differences between Hashcash and Microsoft's email postmark are that postmark hashes the body in addition to the recipient, uses a modified SHA-1 as the hash function, and uses multiple sub-puzzles to reduce proof of work variance.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Like e-mail, blogs often fall victim to comment spam.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Some blog owners have used hashcash scripts written in the JavaScript language to slow down comment spammers.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Some scripts (such as wp-hashcash) claim to implement hashcash but instead depend on JavaScript obfuscation to force the client to generate a matching key; while this does require some processing power, it does not use the hashcash algorithm or hashcash stamps.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] In a digital marketplace, service providers can use hashcash to build reputation to attract clients.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] To build reputation, a service provider first selects a public key as its ID, and then discovers by brute force a nonce that, when concatenated to the ID, results in a hash digest with several leading zeros.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The more zeros, the higher the reputation.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hashcash is not patented, and the reference implementation and most of the other implementations are free software.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] Hashcash is included or available for many Linux distributions.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] RSA Security has made statements on intellectual property rights to the IETF about client-puzzles in the context of an RFC that described client-puzzles (not hashcash).
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] The RFC included hashcash in the title and referenced hashcash, but the mechanism described in it is a known-solution interactive challenge which is more akin to Client-Puzzles; hashcash is non-interactive and therefore does not have a known solution.
[src:proof-of-work/hashcash] In any case RSA's IPR statement can not apply to hashcash because hashcash predates (March 1997) the client-puzzles publication (February 1999) and the client-puzzles patent filing US7197639 (February 2000).
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] In the context of cryptocurrency mining, a **mining pool** is the pooling of resources by miners, who share their processing power over a network, to split the reward equally, according to the amount of work they contributed to the probability of finding a block.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] A "share" is awarded to members of the mining pool who present a valid partial proof-of-work.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Mining in pools began when the difficulty for mining increased to the point where it could take centuries for slower miners to generate a block.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] The solution to this problem was for miners to pool their resources so they could generate blocks more quickly and therefore receive a portion of the block reward on a consistent basis, rather than randomly once every few years.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Share is the principal concept of the mining pool operation.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] So it may be a block solution, but it is not necessarily so.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] For example, suppose a block solution is a number that ends with 10 zeros and, a share may be a number with 5 zeros at the end.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Sooner or later one of the shares will have not only 5, but 10 zeros at the end, and this will be the block solution.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Mining pools need shares to estimate the miner's contribution to the work performed by the pool to find a block.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] There are numerous miner reward systems: PPS, PROP, PPLNS, PPLNT, and many more.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Mining pools may contain hundreds or thousands of miners using specialized protocols.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] In all these schemes B stands for a block reward minus pool fee and p is a probability of finding a block in a share attempt ( $p=1/D$ , where D is current block difficulty).
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] A pool can support "variable share difficulty" feature, which means that a miner can select the share target (the lower bound of share difficulty) on their own and change p accordingly.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] The Pay-per-Share (PPS) approach offers an instant, guaranteed payout to a miner for their contribution to the probability that the pool finds a block.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Miners are paid out from the pool's existing balance and can withdraw their payout immediately.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] This model allows for the least possible variance in payment for miners while also transferring much of the risk to the pool's operator.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Each share costs exactly the expected value of each hash attempt $R=B\cdot p$ .
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Miners earn shares until the pool finds a block (the end of the mining round).
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] After that each user gets reward $R=B\cdot {\frac {n}{N}}$ , where n is amount of their own shares, and N is amount of all shares in this round.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] In other words, all shares are equal, but its value is calculated only at the end of each round.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Pooled mining (BPM), also known as "slush's system", due to its first use on a pool called "slush's pool', uses a system where older shares from the beginning of a block round are given less weight than more recent shares.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] A new round starts the moment the pool solves a block and miners are rewarded **Proportional** to the shares submitted.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] This reduces the ability to cheat the mining pool system by switching pools during a round, to maximize profit.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Pay-per-last-N-shares (PPLNS) method is similar to **Proportional**, but the miner's reward is calculated on a basis of N last shares, instead of all shares for the last round.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] This means that when a block is found, the reward of each miner is calculated based on the miner contribution to the last N pool shares.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Therefore, if the round was short enough all miners get more profit and vice versa.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Solo pools operate the same way as usual pools, with the only difference being that block reward is not distributed among all miners.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] The entire reward in a solo pool goes to the miner who finds the block.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Peer-to-peer mining pool (P2Pool) decentralizes the responsibilities of a pool server, removing the chance of the pool operator cheating or the server being a single point of failure.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Miners work on a side blockchain called a share chain, mining at a lower difficulty at a rate of one share block per 30 seconds.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Once a share block reaches the network target, it is transmitted and merged onto the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Miners are rewarded when this occurs proportional to the shares submitted prior to the target block.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] A P2Pool requires the miners to run a full node, bearing the weight of hardware expenses and network bandwidth.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Geometric Method (GM) was invented by Meni Rosenfeld.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] It is based on the same "score" idea, as Slush's method: the score granted for every new share, relatively to already existing score and the score of future shares, is always the same, thus there is no advantage to mining early or late in the round.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Generalized version of Geometric and PPLNS methods.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] It involves new parameter: o ("cross-round leakage").
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] When $o=0$ this becomes the Geometric method.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] When $o=1$ this becomes a variant of PPLNS, with exponential decay instead of a step function.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Usually, the blocks in the cryptocurrency network contain transactions.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Transaction fees are paid to the miner (mining pool).
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Different mining pools could share these fees between their miners or not.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Pay-per-last-N-shares (PPLNS), Pay-Per-Share Plus (PPS+) or Full Pay-Per-Share (FPPS) are the most fair methods where the payouts from the pool include not only the block subsidy but also the transaction fees.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Open-source monitoring tools allow public analysis of mining pool behavior, including hashrate distribution, block composition, and whether pools include the highest-fee transactions available in the mempool.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Block audit features compare expected block templates — generated using the same transaction selection algorithm as Bitcoin Core — against actual mined blocks.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Discrepancies may indicate transaction prioritization, transaction censorship, or out-of-band fee arrangements such as transaction acceleration services.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Multipools switch between different altcoins and constantly calculate which coin is at that moment the most profitable to mine.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Two key factors are involved in the algorithm that calculates profitability, the block time, and the price on the exchanges.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] To avoid the need for many different wallets for all possible minable coins, multipools may automatically exchange the mined coin to a coin that is accepted in the mainstream (for example bitcoin).
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Using this method, because the most profitable coins are being mined and then sold for the intended coin, it is possible to receive more coins in the intended currency than by mining that currency alone.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] This method also increases demand on the intended coin, which has the side effect of increasing or stabilizing the value of the intended coin.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Some companies that sell hash power may do so by aggregating the work of many small miners (for example, NiceHash), paying them proportionally by share like a pool would.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Some such companies operate their own pools.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] These can be considered multipools, because they usually employ a similar method of work switching, although the work they assign is determined by customer demand rather than "raw" profitability.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] When mining happens the miner simply "looks" through the pre-stored answers and submits the best one found to the network, with minimal energy used to read the hard drives.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] Due to the low hardware specification requirements of the PoC mining process, this type of mining can be conducted on a regular PC still being used for other day-to-day tasks.
[src:proof-of-work/mining-pool] The first PoC blockchain was brought online in 2014 and is known as Signum today, with other PoC chains coming out much later, examples: Chia, Flax, and BitcoinHD.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Proof of work was later popularized by Bitcoin as a foundation for consensus in a permissionless decentralized network, in which miners compete to append blocks and mine new currency, each miner experiencing a success probability proportional to the computational effort expended.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] PoW and PoS (proof of stake) remain the two best known Sybil deterrence mechanisms.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In the context of cryptocurrencies they are the most common mechanisms.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] A key feature of proof-of-work schemes is their asymmetry: the *work* – the computation – must be moderately hard (yet feasible) on the prover or requester side but easy to check for the verifier or service provider.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This idea is also known as a CPU cost function, client puzzle, computational puzzle, or CPU pricing function.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Another common feature is built-in incentive-structures that reward allocating computational capacity to the network with value in the form of cryptocurrency.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The purpose of proof-of-work algorithms is not proving that certain work was carried out or that a computational puzzle was "solved", but deterring manipulation of data by establishing large energy and hardware-control requirements to be able to do so.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Proof-of-work systems have been criticized by some environmentalists who argue that it generates externalities that are not reflected in market electricity prices which do not compensate for the economic and social benefits.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The interruptible load characteristics of proof-of-work mining provide demand-response services and support the integration of variable renewable energy under certain market and grid conditions.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The concept of Proof of Work (PoW) has its roots in early research on combating spam and preventing denial-of-service attacks.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] One of the earliest implementations of PoW was Hashcash, created by British cryptographer Adam Back in 1997.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] It was designed as an anti-spam mechanism that required email senders to perform a small computational task, effectively proving that they expended resources (in the form of CPU time) before sending an email.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This task was trivial for legitimate users but would impose a significant cost on spammers attempting to send bulk messages.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Hashcash's system was based on the concept of finding a hash value that met certain criteria, a task that required computational effort and thus served as a "proof of work." The idea was that by making it computationally expensive to send large volumes of email, spamming would be reduced.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] One popular system, used in Hashcash, uses partial hash inversions to prove that computation was done, as a goodwill token to send an e-mail.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Whether PoW systems can actually solve a particular denial-of-service issue such as the spam problem is subject to debate; the system must make sending spam emails obtrusively unproductive for the spammer, but should also not prevent legitimate users from sending their messages.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In other words, a genuine user should not encounter any difficulties when sending an email, but an email spammer would have to expend a considerable amount of computing power to send out many emails at once.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Proof-of-work systems are being used by other, more complex cryptographic systems such as Bitcoin, which uses a system similar to Hashcash.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Proof of work traces its theoretical origins to early efforts to combat digital abuse, evolving significantly over time to address security, accessibility, and broader applications beyond its initial anti-spam purpose.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The idea first emerged in 1993 as a deterrent for junk mail, but it was Satoshi Nakamoto’s 2008 whitepaper, "Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System," that solidified proof of work's potential as a cornerstone of blockchain networks.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This development reflects the rising demands for secure, trustless systems.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The earliest appearance of proof of work was in 1993, when Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor proposed a system to curb junk email by requiring senders to perform computationally demanding tasks.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In their paper, "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail," they outlined methods such as computing modular square roots, designed to be challenging to solve yet straightforward to verify, establishing a foundational principle of proof of work's asymmetry.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This asymmetry is crucial to the effectiveness of proof of work, ensuring that tasks like sending spam are costly for attackers, while verification remains efficient for legitimate users.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This conceptual groundwork found practical use in 1997 with Adam Back’s Hashcash, a system that required senders to compute a partial hash inversion of the SHA-1 algorithm, producing a hash with a set number of leading zeros.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Bitcoin, launched in 2009 by Satoshi Nakamoto, marked a pivotal shift by adapting Hashcash's proof of work for cryptocurrency.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Nakamoto's Bitcoin whitepaper outlined a system using the SHA-256 algorithm, where miners compete to solve cryptographic puzzles to append blocks to the blockchain, earning rewards in the process.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Unlike Hashcash's static proofs, Bitcoin's proof of work algorithm dynamically adjusts its difficulty based on the average time taken to mine a block in the previous epoch, ensuring a consistent block time of approximately 10 minutes, creating a tamper-proof chain.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This innovation transformed proof of work from a standalone deterrent into a consensus mechanism for a decentralized network, emphasizing financial incentives over computational effort.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Initially mined with standard CPUs, Bitcoin saw a rapid transition to GPUs, then to FPGAs and finally to ASICs, which vastly outperformed general hardware in solving SHA-256 puzzles.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] To address Bitcoin's increasing reliance on specialized hardware, Litecoin changed the Hashcash hash function from SHA-256 to Scrypt.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Developed by Colin Percival and detailed in the technical specification "The scrypt Password-Based Key Derivation Function," Scrypt was designed as a memory-intensive algorithm, requiring a moderate amount of RAM to compute.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Litecoin's goal of making mining more accessible to users with general-purpose hardware didn't last long, as mining followed a similar migration from CPUs through GPUs and FPGAs to ASICs.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] There are two classes of proof-of-work protocols.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Known-solution protocols tend to have slightly lower variance than unbounded probabilistic protocols because the variance of a rectangular distribution is lower than the variance of a Poisson distribution (with the same mean).
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] A generic technique for reducing variance is to use multiple independent sub-challenges, as the average of multiple samples will have a lower variance.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] There are also fixed-cost functions such as the time-lock puzzle.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Finally, some PoW systems offer **shortcut** computations that allow participants who know a secret, typically a private key, to generate cheap PoWs.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The rationale is that mailing-list holders may generate stamps for every recipient without incurring a high cost.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Whether such a feature is desirable depends on the usage scenario.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] At the IACR conference Crypto 2022 researchers presented a paper describing Ofelimos, a blockchain protocol with a consensus mechanism based on "proof of useful work" (PoUW).
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Rather than miners consuming energy in solving complex, but essentially useless, puzzles to validate transactions, Ofelimos achieves consensus while simultaneously providing a decentralized optimization problem solver.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The protocol is built around Doubly Parallel Local Search (DPLS), a local search algorithm that is used as the PoUW component.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The paper gives an example that implements a variant of WalkSAT, a local search algorithm to solve Boolean problems.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Optimisable proof of work (OPoW) is a variant of proof of work in which the proof-of-work algorithms themselves can be optimised without causing network instability or centralisation.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The mechanism incentivises two categories of participants: miners who compute solutions and are rewarded for adopting the most efficient algorithms, and algorithm contributors who develop and submit improved algorithms and earn rewards based on their adoption by miners.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] By decoupling the solving of computational problems from block creation, OPoW allows many solutions to be found per block, effectively creating a synthetic market for algorithms.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In 2009, the Bitcoin network went online.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Bitcoin is a proof-of-work digital currency that, like Finney's RPoW, is also based on the Hashcash PoW.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] But in Bitcoin, double-spend protection is provided by a decentralized P2P protocol for tracking transfers of coins, rather than the hardware trusted computing function used by RPoW.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Bitcoin has better trustworthiness because it is protected by computation.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Bitcoins are "mined" using the Hashcash proof-of-work function by individual miners and verified by the decentralized nodes in the P2P Bitcoin network.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Since the creation of Bitcoin, proof-of-work has been the predominant design of peer-to-peer cryptocurrency.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Studies have estimated the total energy consumption of cryptocurrency mining.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The PoW mechanism requires a vast amount of computing resources, which consume a significant amount of electricity.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] 2018 estimates from the University of Cambridge equate Bitcoin's energy consumption to that of Switzerland.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Each block that is added to the blockchain, starting with the block containing a given transaction, is called a confirmation of that transaction.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Ideally, merchants and services that receive payment in the cryptocurrency should wait for at least one confirmation to be distributed over the network, before assuming that the payment was done.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The more confirmations that the merchant waits for, the more difficult it is for an attacker to successfully reverse the transaction in a blockchain—unless the attacker controls more than half the total network power, in which case it is called a 51% attack.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Within the Bitcoin community there are groups working together in mining pools.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Some miners use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) for PoW.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This trend toward mining pools and specialized ASICs has made mining some cryptocurrencies economically infeasible for most players without access to the latest ASICs, nearby sources of inexpensive energy, or other special advantages.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Some PoWs claim to be ASIC-resistant, i.e. to limit the efficiency gain that an ASIC can have over commodity hardware, like a GPU, to be well under an order of magnitude.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] ASIC resistance has the advantage of keeping mining economically feasible on commodity hardware, but also contributes to the corresponding risk that an attacker can briefly rent access to a large amount of unspecialized commodity processing power to launch a 51% attack against a cryptocurrency.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] By design, Bitcoin's Proof of Work consensus algorithm is vulnerable to Majority Attacks (51% attacks).
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Any miner with over 51% of mining power is able to control the canonical chain until their hash power falls below 50%.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] This allows them to reorg the blockchain, double-spend, censor transactions, and completely control block production.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] There was a notable double-spend on Bitcoin in March 2013 when the chain split due to a bug in the Bitcoin 0.8.0 client.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] While on the 0.8.0 chain, a merchant (OKPAY) confirmed a $10k deposit from a customer.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Bitcoin miners then 51% attacked the network, reverting 24 blocks and reversing the transaction leading to the customer's deposit.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The customer then double-spent the bitcoin on the canonical pre-0.8.0 chain as an experiment.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] A 2025 paper by Duke University Finance Professor Campbell Harvey estimates that a week-long 51% attack on Bitcoin could be executed with only $6 Billion at Oct 2025 prices.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The total cost of attack would be less than 1% of Bitcoin's total value.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] An attacker could profit from shorting Bitcoin or for non-economic reasons.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Bitcoin has asymmetric security where Bitcoin miners control its security, but they aren't the same people who hold Bitcoin.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Unlike with Proof of Stake, there is much weaker economic incentive for those who control security to protect the network under Proof of Work.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Historically, many Proof of Work networks with low security budgets have fallen under 51% attacks., which highlights PoW's asymmetric security.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The amount of protection provided by PoW mining is close to the security budget of the network, which is roughly equal to the total block reward.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] With each additional halving, Bitcoin's security budget continues to fall relative to its market cap.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In the past, Bitcoin developers were hopeful that transaction fees would rise to replace the declining block subsidy, but this has not been the case as transaction fees still only generate 1% of the total block reward.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] There are concerns that Bitcoin's security is unsustainable in the long run due to the declining security budget caused by its halvings.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Miners compete to solve crypto challenges on the bitcoin blockchain, and their solutions must be agreed upon by all nodes and reach consensus.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The solutions are then used to validate transactions, add blocks and generate new bitcoins.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Miners are rewarded for solving these puzzles and successfully adding new blocks.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] However, the Bitcoin-style mining process is very energy intensive because the proof of work is shaped like a lottery mechanism.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The underlying computational work has no other use but to provide security to the network that provides open access and has to work in adversarial conditions.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Miners have to use a lot of energy to add a new block containing a transaction to the blockchain.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] The energy used in this competition is what fundamentally gives Bitcoin its level of security and resistance to attacks.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Also, miners have to invest computer hardwares that need large spaces as fixed cost.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In January 2022 vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority Erik Thedéen called on the EU to ban the proof of work model in favor of the proof of stake model due its lower energy emissions.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] In November 2022 the state of New York enacted a two-year moratorium on cryptocurrency mining that does not completely use renewable energy as a power source for two years.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] Existing mining companies will be grandfathered in to continue mining without the use of renewable energy but they will not be allowed to expand or renew permits with the state.
[src:proof-of-work/proof-of-work] No new mining companies that do not completely use renewable energy will be allowed to begin mining.
